# pseudocron-large.cfg.example — pgai-agent-kanban pseudocron schedule: LARGE tier
#
# Hardware assumption: 8+ cores / 16+ GB RAM, dedicated high-throughput host.
#
# Tier: large
# Cadence: every minute, all five agents, fired every minute.
#   - PM     fires at every minute: 0,1,2,...,59
#   - CM     fires at every minute: 0,1,2,...,59
#   - TESTER fires at every minute: 0,1,2,...,59
#   - CODER  fires at every minute: 0,1,2,...,59
#   - WRITER fires at every minute: 0,1,2,...,59
#
# Crontab-to-pseudocron mapping:
#   crontab-large fires all agents every minute with sub-minute sleep staggers
#   to enforce a pipeline ordering within each minute cycle.  Pseudocron has no
#   sleep/stagger field; sub-minute offsets are collapsed to minute granularity:
#
#     crontab: PM     * * * * * --sleep=0   -> every minute (unchanged)
#     crontab: CODER  * * * * * --sleep=12  -> every minute, staggered +12s via --sleep (preserved)
#     crontab: CM     * * * * * --sleep=24  -> every minute, staggered +24s via --sleep (preserved)
#     crontab: WRITER * * * * * --sleep=36  -> every minute, staggered +36s via --sleep (preserved)
#     crontab: TESTER * * * * * --sleep=48  -> every minute, staggered +48s via --sleep (preserved)
#
#   Result: all five agents fire at every minute simultaneously.  The crontab
#   pipeline ordering (PM -> CODER -> CM -> WRITER -> TESTER, interleaved by
#   sleep offset) IS preserved: --sleep is a wake-batch flag, carried on each job line.  wake-batch.sh's
#   own work-queue locking provides serialization.  On a high-core host, the
#   risk of lock collision is low since agents are non-blocking workers.
#
# Maximum agent-to-agent handoff latency: ~1 minute.
# Best-case handoff: sub-minute (same firing cycle, via wake-batch.sh locking).
# Recommended for: 8+ core dedicated servers, high-throughput CI machines,
#   production kanban instances requiring minimum RC latency.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------
# REQUIRED pseudocron.env EXPORTS
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------
# When paired with install-pseudocron.sh, pseudocron.env must contain:
#
#   export PGAI_AGENT_KANBAN_ROOT_PATH=/path/to/pgai_agent_kanban
#       # Full path to the installed kanban root.  All wake scripts derive
#       # their paths from this variable.
#
#   export PATH=/usr/local/bin:/usr/bin:/bin
#       # Ensure wake-batch.sh and its dependencies are on PATH.
#       # Adjust if claude or other tools are installed to non-standard paths.
#
#   export HOME=/home/your-user
#       # Required when pseudocron is launched from a system init (systemd unit,
#       # etc.) that does not set HOME.  Wake scripts and claude may need HOME.
#
#   export ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=<your-api-key>
#       # Anthropic API key consumed by claude.  Required unless the API key
#       # is injected via another mechanism (e.g. a secrets manager wrapper).
#
# Optional: override a role's model (per-role; provider-agnostic)
#   export PGAI_CODER_MODEL=<model-id>
#   export PGAI_PM_MODEL=<model-id>
#       # Recognized roles: PM, CODER, WRITER, TESTER, CM
#
# Copy team/scripts/pseudocron.env.example to
# $PGAI_AGENT_KANBAN_ROOT_PATH/pseudocron.env and fill in real values.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# Install:
#   cp team/templates/install/pseudocron-large.cfg.example \
#      "$PGAI_AGENT_KANBAN_ROOT_PATH/pseudocron.cfg"
#
# Commands are ROOT-RELATIVE: pseudocron.py sets cwd to the kanban root before
# executing each job, so "scripts/wake-batch.sh ..." resolves to the correct
# absolute path regardless of where pseudocron.py was launched from.

# =============================================================================
# LARGE-TIER PATTERN — every-minute firing for all five agents
#                      (sub-minute pipeline ordering collapsed to minute level)
# =============================================================================
# Maximum wait between agent firings: 1 minute
# Best-case agent-to-agent handoff: sub-minute (via wake-batch.sh locking)
#
# Operator tuning:
#   - To reduce API call volume, switch to every-2-minutes by removing odd or
#     even minutes from each agent's list (equivalent to medium tier).
#   - If API rate limits are hit, reduce cadence or stagger agents by
#     distributing across alternating minutes (use medium tier as a reference).

# --- PM: fires every minute (all 60 minutes) ---
0  scripts/wake-batch.sh --agent=pm     --sleep=0 >> logs/cron-pm.log 2>&1
1  scripts/wake-batch.sh --agent=pm     --sleep=0 >> logs/cron-pm.log 2>&1
2  scripts/wake-batch.sh --agent=pm     --sleep=0 >> logs/cron-pm.log 2>&1
